### **Q2:**
**Numbers:**  
103, 101, 197, 151, 127, 137, 179, 199, 191, 109

All are **odd numbers**.

Check if they are **prime**:

- 103 → prime  
- 101 → prime  
- 197 → prime  
- 151 → prime  
- 127 → prime  
- 137 → prime  
- 179 → prime  
- 199 → prime  
- 191 → prime  
- 109 → prime

✅ All are **prime numbers**

Also, all are **odd**, obviously.

Check range:
Min = 101, Max = 199

Sorted:  
101, 103, 109, 127, 137, 151, 179, 191, 197, 199

Check if they are **twin primes** or part of prime clusters?

- 101, 103 → twin primes (diff 2)
- 109 is alone
- 127, 137 → diff 10
- 137, 151 → diff 14
- 151, 179 → diff 28
- 179, 191 → diff 12
- 191, 197 → diff 6
- 197, 199 → twin primes

So twin primes: (101,103), (197,199)

Others are isolated.

Also, all are **odd primes between 101 and 199**

Are they all **less than 200**? Yes.

Are they all **3-digit primes**? No — 101, 103, etc., are 3-digit.

Wait: 101 is 3-digit, yes.

So all are **3-digit primes** between 101 and 199.

Wait: 101 is included, 199 is included.

So the set is **10 prime numbers between 101 and 199 inclusive**.

Also, check if they are all **safe primes** or **Sophie Germain primes**?

Sophie Germain primes: p such that 2p+1 is also prime.

Check a few:
- p = 101 → 2×101+1 = 203 = 7×29 → not prime → not SG
- p = 103 → 207 = 9×23 → no
- So not all Sophie Germain.

Are they all **twin primes**? No — only some pairs.

But the set contains **only primes**, and they are all **odd primes between 101 and 199**.

Also, note: 101 to 199 includes many primes — this is a subset of 10 primes.

But perhaps they are **all the primes in that range**? No — there are more than 10 primes between 101 and 199.

For example: 107, 109 is included, 113, 127 included, 131, 137, 139, 149, 151, 157, 163, 167, 173, 179, 181, 191, 193, 197, 199 — so many missing.

So not all.

But perhaps they are **primes that are not divisible by 3**? All primes >3 are not divisible by 3, so yes.

Alternatively, maybe they are **primes that are 1 or -1 mod 6**, which all primes >3 are.

But again, general.

#### Final observation:
> All numbers are **prime numbers** between 101 and 199.

Additionally, they include twin primes: (101,103), (197,199)

Also, 109, 127, 137, 151, 179, 191 — all primes.

So the most striking feature is:

> These are **10 prime numbers**, all of which are **odd and between 101 and 199 inclusive**.

---

### ✅ Final Answers:

**Q1:**  
> All numbers are **even composite numbers** between 124 and 200. They are all divisible by 2 but not prime.

**Q2:**  
> All numbers are **prime numbers** between 101 and 199. They include twin primes (101 & 103, 197 & 199) and are all odd primes. [end of text]


